# Code Review Process

## Before reviewing

1. Read `docs/REVIEW.md` first. It contains the last review's findings, metrics, and known-accepted issues.
2. Do NOT re-discover known-accepted issues listed there. Focus on:
   - **Regressions**: Did any previously-fixed issue return?
   - **New issues**: Anything introduced since the last review.
   - **Metric changes**: Run `tsc --noEmit`, `eslint .`, `vitest run`, `vite build` and compare against stored metrics.
3. Check `git log --oneline` since the last review date to scope what changed.

## Review checklist

- [ ] TypeScript: `npx tsc --noEmit` — 0 errors
- [ ] Lint: `npx eslint .` — 0 errors, 0 warnings
- [ ] Tests: `npx vitest run` — all pass, no skipped
- [ ] Build: `npx vite build` — succeeds, no chunk > 500 KB
- [ ] No new `@ts-ignore`, `eslint-disable`, or type assertions (`as`)
- [ ] No hardcoded colors in themed components (CV preview is an exception)
- [ ] New features have tests
- [ ] Accessibility: aria-labels, keyboard nav, focus management
- [ ] Bundle: lazy imports for heavy libraries (docx, genai)

## After reviewing

1. Update `docs/REVIEW.md`:
   - Bump the date
   - Add a new review section with findings
   - Move fixed issues to resolved, add new issues
   - Update metrics
2. Rate the codebase out of 10 with brief justification.

## Cost optimisation

- Use `git diff` and `git log` to scope changes since last review — avoid re-reading unchanged files.
- Run automated checks (tsc, eslint, vitest, build) first. Only read source files if checks fail or to investigate new code.
- The review doc has architecture notes — don't re-explore the codebase structure unless it changed.
